        public static final Types.Commands Reset
        Commands: Wifi
        Devices: S910 - 3D
        reset user calibration. Sets calibration values that have been determined by the user back to the "Default" value and stores the data in flash. The "Default" value corresponds with the delivered state of the device (ex-works)

        parameter
        answer: ruc: (ok | <error>)
        parameter:
        0 (ALL) reset all data (in all subsystems)
        4 (CCO) Subsystem "Calculate coordinates"
        5 (LEV) Subsystem "Level"
        6 (MON) Subsystem "Monitor"
        7 (CAM) Subsystem "Camera"
        8 (CMD) Subsystem "CMD"

      • PIN

        public static final Types.Commands PIN
        Commands: Wifi
        Devices: S910 - 3D
        PIN code entry. The PIN code can be changed by the user when the device has the PIN status "inactive" or "active"
        Inactive PIN code = 0000
        If a PIN code > 0000 is set, the device is in PIN status "PIN required" Following the entry of a valid PIN code [pin c ****] (max. 3 tries), the PIN status changes to "active". Now the device is unlocked and the PIN code can also be changed with the command [pin s ****]. If the PIN code is entered incorrectly 3 times, then the current PIN code becomes invalid and the device changes into the PIN status "PUK required". If a valid PUK code is entered (max. 2 tries), the PIN code is set to 0000 and the device is unlocked
        answer: pin: ! pin: ! pin: @E000
        ResponsePlain

      • PUK

        public static final Types.Commands PUK
        Commands: Wifi
        Devices: 3D
        PUK code entry.
        The entry (check) of the PUK code is then required if the customer has activated the PIN code (PIN entry required) and incorrectly entered the PIN code 3 times. The PIN code is reset to 0000 by the entry of a valid PUK code [puk c ********]. If the PUK code is entered incorrectly 2 times, then the device is locked (PIN status "device locked"). There are then very few commands available. The device must be switched off (either by the ON button on the sensor or by the command "b"). After switching on the device, it goes automatically back into the PIN status "PUK required"

        Command: puk "parameter1" "parameter2"
        parameter1: c (check) PUK code check
        parameter2: [10000000..99999999]
        Response: OK: !, Error: @E(number)
        answer: puk: !
        ResponsePlain

      • PositionAbsolute

        public static final Types.Commands PositionAbsolute
        Commands: Wifi
        Devices: 3D
        Starts absolute positioning..
        Comment: The commands [pv] "Position velocity" and [pd] "Position direction" have no influence on the [pa] command.Positioning is always done at a preset speed (cannot be changed).The system automatically chooses the shortest path (taking into account the blocked angle range in the vertical circle). Either one motor (Hz or V) or both motors can be started at the same time. The answer "ok" is returned if the motor(s) has/have been started (standard setting). If the motor has reached the intended position, an event is triggered at a second TCP port.If only one motor was started, then the second motor can be started directly after the receipt of the answer (to the first command).The command [gms] "Get motor status" can be used to query whether the motor has reached the position.
        command: pa (id:real | id:real )
        answer: pa: (ok | error)
        id: Hz Intended position horizontal angle
        V Intended position vertical angle
        NI_Hz Intended position horizontal angle (not tilt-corrected)
        NI_V Intended position vertical angle (not tilt-corrected)
        Attention: Either the tilt-corrected or the non-tilt-corrected values can be transferred. A combination of values is not allowed
        NO RESPONSE
        Usage: List<String> positionParameters = new ArrayList<String>();
        positionParameters.add("23:"+hz);
        positionParameters.add("24:"+v);
        currentDevice.sendCommand(Types.Commands.PositionAbsolute,positionParameters);

        public static final Types.Commands LiveImage

        This command must be sent to the UDP server.. The answer is sent to the address of the UDP client.         < P_Orient > short (36 + 2 byte)
        < dummy > short (38 + 2 byte) // not used < Counter > short (40 + 4 byte)
        < Time [sec] > short (44 + 4 byte)
        < Time [nsec] > short (48 + 4 byte)
        <image> jpeg
        ResponseImage
